data.9285a794-bb18-11ea-85a6-3af9d3b32b71: The San Francisco Museum of Modern Art (SFMOMA) is a modern and contemporary art museum located in San Francisco, California. A nonprofit organization, SFMOMA holds an internationally recognized collection of modern and contemporary art, and was the first museum on the West Coast devoted solely to 20th-century art. The museum's current collection includes over 33,000 works of painting, sculpture, photography, architecture, design, and media arts, and moving into the 21st century

data.c6dc8936-bb18-11ea-85a6-3af9d3b32b71: The Mexican Communist Party (Spanish: Partido Comunista Mexicano, PCM) was a communist party in Mexico. It was founded in 1917 as the Socialist Workers' Party (Partido Socialista Obrero, PSO) by Manabendra Nath Roy, a left-wing Indian revolutionary. The PSO changed its name to the Mexican Communist Party in November 1919.

data.c0a14a2e-bba0-11ea-ad92-3af9d3b32b71: After its poor showing and a two decade-long period of moderation during which it adopted a "Eurocommunist" position, the PCM merged with three other far-left political parties in November 1981 and became the Unified Socialist Party of Mexico (PSUM).

The Louvre or the Louvre Museum, is a national art museum in Paris, France. It is located on the Right Bank of the Seine in the city's 1st arrondissement (district or ward) and home to some of the most canonical works of Western art, including the Mona Lisa and the Venus de Milo.

data.9285a794-bb18-11ea-85a6-3af9d3b32b71: The Musée National d'Art Moderne is the national museum for modern art of France. It is located in Paris and is housed in the Centre Pompidou in the 4th arrondissement of the city. In 2021 it ranked 10th in the list of most visited art museums in the world, with 1,501,040 visitors. It is one of the largest museums for modern and contemporary art.

The Seminario de Cultura Mexicana is an institution made up of great personalities from culture, sciences and humanities who share their knowledge in different states of the Republic through conferences, discussions, exhibitions and workshops.

On February 28, 1942, by Presidential Agreement and initiative of the Ministry of Public Education, 19 intellectuals of the time were invited to form the founding group of the Seminar of Mexican Culture, among whom were Manuel M. Ponce, Frida Kahlo, Mariano Azuela, among others. Since then, the Seminar has continued to be made up of great personalities who promote the circulation of works with artistic, scientific and humanistic content, from a multidisciplinary perspective that promotes activities in different spheres of the exact sciences, social sciences and humanities.

The founding of the Seminar of Mexican Culture meant the creation of culture as a link between the different entities of the country and its people. Undoubtedly, seminarians have become a shining army of wise people who have worked to enrich human life
